<div class="section-two-tr">
	<div class="intro-tr poem-share">
		“The god is inside the stone, vacuous exercet aera morsus. The force is arrested, but there is never any question about its latency, about the force being the essential, and the rest ‘accidental’ in the philosophic technical sense. The shape occurs.” <br><br>
		Ezra Pound, Cavalcanti, 152
	</div>
</div>
<div class="video-space vid1"></div>
<div class="poem1-tr poem-tr poem-share">
	We wandered like stray dogs, barking<br> 
	back at bands of bitches, flicking<br>  
	cheap lighters and dull switchblades, lips<br>  
	still wet from the black liquorish liquor,<br> 
	and chips dipped in yogurt saltwater. 
</div>
<div class="video-space vid2"></div>
<div class="poem2-tr poem-tr poem-share">
	We spoke in riddles like tricksters, snaking<br>
	credit cards from fanny packers and danced<br>
	on the beach to the new blues while<br>
	the clean sun sweat over everything and<br>
	I spent hours shaking the sand off my shoes. 

</div>
<div class="video-space vid3"></div>
<div class="poem3-tr poem-tr poem-share">
	There is no need to sleep, being a dream,<br> 
	peeing behind Coca-Cola machines.<br> 
	And I still smile to remember after,<br> 
	those moments of my life made of <%= link_to 'laughter', '/exile.html', class:"hover-link" %>.

</div>